{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622442"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:02:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:02:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16799"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16799"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.53,0.08,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76697"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9490"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62189"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5159"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"11209"},{"type":"tags","id":"11210"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76697"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBarbiturates were historically used as sedative medications but have largely been replaced by safer alternatives due to their narrow therapeutic window and risk of dependence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of barbiturates?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase GABA release from presynaptic neurons","Potentiate the effect of GABA at the GABA(A) receptor","Block voltage-gated sodium channels on the presynaptic neuron","Block GABA degradation in the synaptic cleft","Partial antagonist at the GABA(A) receptor"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBarbiturates primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epotentiating the effect of GABA at the GABA(A) receptor\u003C/strong\u003E. They bind to the GABA(A) receptor, but not at the GABA site. When barbiturates bind to the GABA(A) receptor, they increase the effect that GABA has when it then binds to the GABA(A) receptor, increasing the duration of chloride channel opening and therefore increasing chloride ion influx into neurons. This leads to hyperpolarisation and reduced neuronal excitability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease GABA release from presynaptic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E - Barbiturates act directly on GABA receptors rather than affecting GABA release\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlock voltage-gated sodium channels on the presynaptic neuron\u003C/strong\u003E - While some anticonvulsants work through this mechanism, this is not how barbiturates function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlock GABA degradation in the synaptic cleft\u003C/strong\u003E - Barbiturates do not affect GABA metabolism or clearance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial antagonist at the GABA(A) receptor\u003C/strong\u003E - Barbiturates enhance rather than oppose GABA effects\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt high concentrations, barbiturates can also directly activate GABA receptors without GABA present, contributing to their potential for fatal overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Barbiturates enhance inhibitory neurotransmission by binding to specific sites on GABA-A receptors, distinct from the GABA binding site.","The main effect of barbiturates is to potentiate the effects of GABA, by increasing the duration of chloride channel opening when GABA binds to its receptor.","At toxic doses, barbiturates can directly activate GABA receptors without GABA present."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62189"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16799"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62189"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T10:44:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T10:45:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9490"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76697"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t